  <mads:note type="source">Smith's Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology, Vol ,
      1867, p. 1: "Callinicus, surnamed Sutoroius, a Greek sophist and rhetorician, was a native of
      Syria.....He taught rhetoric at Athens...."</mads:note>
  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "Callinicus, 2, Rhetor, According to the Suda, he was
      a rival of Genethlius (Suda s.v. &#x393;&#x3B5;&#x3BD;&#x3AD;&#x3B8;&#x3BB;&#x3B9;&#x3BF;&#x3C2;) and taught rhetoric in Athens (comp. Lib. Vita
      1.11). He wrote &#x2018;enkomia and orations&#x2019; (cf. Menander Rhetor 386, 30 Sp. for an epibat&#x1E17;rios),
      namely a treatise &#x3A0;&#x3B5;&#x3C1;&#x1F76; &#x3C4;&#x1FC6;&#x3C2; &#x1FEC;&#x3C9;&#x3BC;&#x3B1;&#x3AF;&#x3C9;&#x3BD; &#x1F00;&#x3BD;&#x3B1;&#x3BD;&#x3B5;&#x3CE;&#x3C3;&#x3B5;&#x3C9;&#x3C2; (&#x2018;On the Revival of the Romans&#x2019;)...." from
      Bowie, Ewen (Oxford). "Callinicus." Brill's New Pauly. Antiquity volumes edited by: Hubert
      Cancik and Helmuth Schneider . Brill, 2008. Brill Online. Tufts University Library. 16
      December 2008</mads:note>
